---
globs: apps/worker/worker/jobs/publish.py, apps/web/app/api/**/*.ts, apps/web/**/*.tsx
alwaysApply: false
---

Use these rules for YouTube, TikTok, OAuth, scheduled uploads, and connected creator accounts.

Publishing is a later-stage feature. Do not implement TikTok before core clipping, rendering, and YouTube flow are stable.

Accounts:
- Store connected platform accounts in the accounts table.
- OAuth tokens must be encrypted or protected appropriately.
- Never expose access tokens or refresh tokens to the client.
- Never log OAuth tokens.
- Validate account ownership before publishing.

Scheduled publishing:
- A scheduled upload should create or update a publish job.
- publish jobs should use run_after or an equivalent scheduling field.
- The worker should only execute publish jobs when their scheduled time has arrived.
- Publishing should update job status and clip/platform status.

YouTube:
- Use OAuth.
- Upload generated clip files only after verifying file existence.
- Support title, description, thumbnail, visibility, and scheduled time where possible.
- Handle quota and API errors gracefully.

TikTok:
- Treat TikTok publishing as a later integration.
- Expect API approval, OAuth scopes, and platform restrictions.
- Do not assume TikTok upload works the same as YouTube.

Safety and rights:
- Only publish content the user owns or is authorized to publish.
- Avoid auto-publishing without clear user confirmation.
- For MVP, prefer schedule after user review rather than fully autonomous posting.

Do not:
- Store platform credentials in .env if they are user-specific OAuth tokens.
- Put publishing logic in UI components.
- Publish failed or partially rendered clips.
- Claim a clip was uploaded unless the platform API confirms success.
